---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import MoonStar from '../components/decor/MoonStar.astro';
import Sparkles from '../components/decor/Sparkles.astro';
import WavyDivider from '../components/decor/WavyDivider.astro';
import Dashboard from '../components/TeamPulse/Dashboard';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Manager Dashboard"
  description="A manager's view of one training assignment, with AI that turns the xAPI into a follow-up plan and Slack coaching nudges."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-paper paper-bg">
    <MoonStar class="absolute top-10 left-6 sm:left-12 w-10 sm:w-14 h-auto opacity-90 hidden sm:block" />
    <Sparkles class="hidden md:block absolute bottom-10 right-10 w-28 lg:w-36 h-auto opacity-80 pointer-events-none" />

    <div class="relative max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 py-16 sm:py-20">
      <p class="font-display text-sm uppercase tracking-widest text-cocoa/50 mb-3">From statements to a decision</p>
      <h1 class="font-display font-semibold text-cocoa text-4xl sm:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-tight tracking-tight">
        The dashboard a <span class="italic text-primary-600">manager</span> actually opens.
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-cocoa/75 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        Most learning dashboards bury managers in charts. This one leads with the four things they came for:
        who's done, how they scored, who needs a nudge, how long they've got. Then it does what a completion
        report can't. It reads the raw xAPI, finds the exposure hiding in the answers, and drafts the follow-up.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-6 inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full border border-cocoa/15 bg-cream-50 px-4 py-1.5 text-xs font-semibold text-cocoa/70 font-display uppercase tracking-widest">
        <span class="inline-block w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-accent-500"></span>
        Synthetic team · real xAPI data shapes
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <WavyDivider />

  <!-- The dashboard itself -->
  <section class="bg-cream-50 py-12 sm:py-16">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6">
      <Dashboard client:load />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- About the data -->
  <section class="bg-paper border-t border-cocoa/10 py-14">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="rounded-3xl border border-cocoa/15 bg-cream-50 p-7 sm:p-9">
        <h2 class="font-display font-semibold text-cocoa text-2xl mb-3">
          About this demo
        </h2>
        <p class="text-cocoa/75 leading-relaxed mb-3">
          The team is fictional, but the data is shaped exactly like aggregated LRS output: one assignment, a roster
          of learners, per-person <span class="font-mono text-sm">launched / progressed / answered / passed / completed</span>
          statements, quiz scores, and the free-text answers people actually typed. The completion rate looks healthy.
          The risk is hiding in three of those answers. That's the whole point.
        </p>
        <p class="text-cocoa/75 leading-relaxed">
          The AI step calls a live model when one is available and falls back to authored output otherwise, so the
          analysis is reproducible here. In a real engagement it reads the same xAPI statements posted to a client LRS,
          and the Slack messages go out through a webhook. The draft-and-approve flow stays exactly as shown.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
